  - q: "Why do French Bulldog puppies need special feeding?"
    a: "Three breed traits shape the brief, and they're linked. First, the flat (brachycephalic) face means a Frenchie gulps air as it eats — aerophagia — which, combined with a tendency to ferment hard-to-digest ingredients, makes the breed famous for flatulence, soft stools and bloating. French Bulldogs have among the highest rates of digestive upset of any breed, so a highly digestible, low-residue food with prebiotic fibre matters enormously. Second, that same gut sensitivity feeds the skin: Frenchies are one of the top breeds for food-triggered skin trouble, and their facial and body folds trap moisture and flare into infections when the diet inflames them. Third, they overheat easily and are prone to weight gain, so keeping a Frenchie lean from puppyhood protects both breathing and joints."
